{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0171h1jpe4BnQvbtiCwHPhxC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0118iWSUuYVi3L5hK6htUCZJ","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/plan.md","content":"# RabbitMQ Cluster Change / Migration Plan\n\n**Prepared:** 2026-06-25  \n**Namespace:** `karma-rabbitmq-change-plan-only-20260-6b2c6ff9`  \n**Author:** Operations Team  \n\n---\n\n## 1. Current Cluster State (as-found)\n\n### 1.1 Software Versions\n| Component | Current | Support Status |\n|-----------|---------|----------------|\n| RabbitMQ  | 3.12.14 | **Out of support** |\n| Erlang/OTP | 25.3.2.15 | Out of support for RabbitMQ 4.x |\n| Container image | `rabbitmq:3.12-management` | — |\n\n### 1.2 Topology\n- **Nodes:** 3 (rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2) — all disk nodes\n- **Network partitions:** none\n- **Alarms:** none\n- **StatefulSet replicas:** 3\n\n### 1.3 Virtual Hosts\n| Name | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `/`  | Default vhost (unused by application) |\n| `/app` | Application vhost |\n\n### 1.4 Users and Permissions\n| User | Tags | `/` vhost | `/app` vhost |\n|------|------|-----------|--------------|\n| `admin` | administrator | configure=`.*` write=`.*` read=`.*` | configure=`.*` write=`.*` read=`.*` |\n| `app-user` | _(none)_ | _(no access)_ | configure=`.*` write=`.*` read=`.*` |\n\n### 1.5 Policies\nNo policies are defined on either vhost.\n\n### 1.6 Queues\n| Vhost | Name | Type | Durable | Auto-delete | Arguments |\n|-------|------|------|---------|-------------|-----------|\n| `/app` | `app-queue` | **classic** | true | false | _(none)_ |\n\nNo queues exist on the `/` vhost.\n\n### 1.7 Exchanges (`/app` vhost)\nOnly standard AMQP built-in exchanges are present (amq.direct, amq.fanout, amq.topic, amq.headers, amq.match, amq.rabbitmq.trace, default direct). No custom exchanges.\n\n### 1.8 Feature Flags (all enabled)\n`quorum_queue`, `stream_queue`, `feature_flags_v2`, `classic_mirrored_queue_version`, `classic_queue_type_delivery_support`, `maintenance_mode_status`, and others — all enabled.\n\n### 1.9 Enabled Plugins\n`rabbitmq_management`, `rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s`, `rabbitmq_management_agent`, `rabbitmq_web_dispatch`, `amqp_client`, `cowboy`, `cowlib`\n\n---\n\n## 2. Identified Gaps and Risks\n\n| # | Area | Finding | Severity |\n|---|------|---------|----------|\n| G1 | Version | RabbitMQ 3.12 is **out of support** — no security patches | High |\n| G2 | Erlang | Erlang 25 is incompatible with RabbitMQ 4.x | High |\n| G3 | Queue type | `app-queue` is a **classic** queue — no replication, no raft-based durability | High |\n| G4 | Policies | No HA, TTL, dead-letter, or overflow policies set | Medium |\n| G5 | Permissions | `app-user` has `configure=.*` on `/app` — can create/delete queues and exchanges | Medium |\n| G6 | Permissions | `admin` has full access to the default `/` vhost, which is otherwise unused | Low |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Proposed Changes\n\n### 3.1 Version Upgrade Path\n\nRabbitMQ requires sequential minor-version upgrades; skipping is not supported.\n\n```\n3.12.14  →  3.13.x  →  4.0.x  →  4.1.x (latest stable)\n```\n\nEach hop is a **rolling upgrade** (one node at a time) with the cluster remaining operational.\n\n**Required Erlang upgrade:**\n- RabbitMQ 3.13 requires Erlang 26+\n- RabbitMQ 4.x requires Erlang 26+\n- Erlang upgrade must accompany the 3.12 → 3.13 step\n\n**Container image sequence:**\n```\nrabbitmq:3.12-management   →  rabbitmq:3.13-management\nrabbitmq:3.13-management   →  rabbitmq:4.0-management\nrabbitmq:4.0-management    →  rabbitmq:4.1-management  (if targeting latest)\n```\n\n**Pre-upgrade checklist (each hop):**\n1. Confirm all feature flags enabled: `rabbitmqctl list_feature_flags`\n2. Enable any new flags introduced in the target version before starting nodes on the new version\n3. Check deprecated features in the target version's release notes\n4. Take a definitions export (backup): `rabbitmqctl export_definitions /tmp/definitions.json`\n\n### 3.2 Queue Migration: Classic → Quorum\n\n`app-queue` must be migrated from `classic` to `quorum` type. Classic queues have no replication; a single-node failure loses unacknowledged messages.\n\n**Migration procedure (zero-downtime, requires application cooperation):**\n1. Create a new quorum queue alongside the existing classic queue:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl declare_queue --vhost /app --name app-queue-quorum --type quorum --durable true\n   ```\n2. Update application publishers to dual-publish to both queues during the cutover window.\n3. Drain `app-queue` (wait for messages in-flight to be consumed and acknowledged).\n4. Switch consumers to `app-queue-quorum`.\n5. Stop dual-publishing; delete `app-queue` (classic) once empty and idle.\n6. Optionally rename `app-queue-quorum` → `app-queue` if the application uses a hard-coded name (requires a brief outage or another rename-by-recreate cycle).\n\n**Quorum queue declaration arguments to apply:**\n```json\n{\n  \"x-queue-type\": \"quorum\",\n  \"x-quorum-initial-group-size\": 3\n}\n```\n\n### 3.3 Policy Additions\n\nApply the following policies to `/app` after the queue migration:\n\n| Policy Name | Pattern | Apply-to | Definition | Priority |\n|-------------|---------|---------|-----------|---------|\n| `ha-quorum` | `^app-` | queues | `{\"x-queue-type\":\"quorum\"}` | 0 |\n| `message-ttl` | `^app-` | queues | `{\"message-ttl\":86400000}` (24 h) | 0 |\n| `dead-letter` | `^app-` | queues | `{\"dead-letter-exchange\":\"amq.direct\",\"dead-letter-routing-key\":\"app-queue-dlq\"}` | 0 |\n| `overflow-drop` | `^app-` | queues | `{\"overflow\":\"drop-head\",\"max-length\":100000}` | 0 |\n\nAlso create a dead-letter queue `app-queue-dlq` (quorum, durable) to receive undeliverable messages.\n\n### 3.4 Permission Hardening\n\n#### Restrict `app-user` on `/app`\nCurrent: configure=`.*` write=`.*` read=`.*`  \nProposed: configure=`^$` (no configure rights) write=`.*` read=`.*`\n\nRationale: application services should publish and consume but must not create or delete queues/exchanges at runtime.\n\n```bash\nrabbitmqctl set_permissions -p /app app-user \"^$\" \".*\" \".*\"\n```\n\n#### Revoke `admin` access to `/` vhost (optional)\nThe default `/` vhost is unused. Revoking `admin`'s permissions there reduces the blast radius of credential compromise. If any tooling relies on the default vhost, skip this step.\n\n```bash\nrabbitmqctl clear_permissions -p / admin\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Upgrade Execution Sequence\n\n### Phase 0 — Preparation (pre-change-window)\n1. Export cluster definitions as backup: `rabbitmqctl export_definitions /tmp/definitions-$(date +%Y%m%d).json`\n2. Confirm all three nodes are healthy and synchronized\n3. Verify application can tolerate rolling restarts (connections re-establish within 30 s)\n4. Review RabbitMQ 3.13 and 4.x release notes for breaking changes relevant to this config\n5. Pre-pull new container images on all Kubernetes nodes to minimize restart delay\n\n### Phase 1 — Erlang + 3.12 → 3.13 Rolling Upgrade\n1. Update StatefulSet image to `rabbitmq:3.13-management`\n2. Use `updateStrategy: RollingUpdate` with `maxUnavailable: 1`\n3. Watch each pod restart: `kubectl rollout status statefulset/rabbitmq`\n4. After each node rejoins: `rabbitmqctl cluster_status` — confirm 3 running nodes before proceeding\n5. After all three nodes on 3.13: `rabbitmqctl enable_feature_flag all`\n\n### Phase 2 — 3.13 → 4.0 Rolling Upgrade\n1. Enable all 3.13 feature flags if not already done\n2. Update StatefulSet image to `rabbitmq:4.0-management`\n3. Repeat rolling upgrade procedure from Phase 1\n4. Confirm feature flags post-upgrade: `rabbitmqctl list_feature_flags`\n\n### Phase 3 — Queue and Policy Migration\n1. Create `app-queue-quorum` (quorum type) alongside existing `app-queue`\n2. Coordinate dual-publish cutover with application team\n3. Drain and delete `app-queue` (classic) once empty\n4. Apply policies listed in §3.3\n5. Apply permission change for `app-user` (§3.4)\n\n### Phase 4 — Validation\n1. `rabbitmqctl cluster_status` — all 3 nodes running, no partitions, no alarms\n2. `rabbitmqctl list_queues -p /app name type state` — `app-queue` shows as `quorum`, state `running`\n3. `rabbitmqctl list_policies -p /app` — 4 policies present\n4. `rabbitmqctl list_permissions -p /app` — `app-user` configure column is `^$`\n5. Send and consume a test message end-to-end\n6. Export final definitions as post-change snapshot\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rollback Plan\n\n| Phase | Rollback Action |\n|-------|----------------|\n| Phase 1 (3.12→3.13) | Downgrade is **not supported** once a node has booted on 3.13 and written data. Mitigation: keep a definitions export and a snapshot of the PVC before upgrade. |\n| Phase 2 (3.13→4.0) | Same constraint — forward-only after first boot on 4.0. |\n| Phase 3 (queue migration) | Classic `app-queue` still exists until explicitly deleted; revert application to publish/consume to/from it. |\n| Phase 4 (permissions) | Re-apply original permissions: `set_permissions -p /app app-user \".*\" \".*\" \".*\"` |\n\n> **Key rollback constraint:** RabbitMQ does not support downgrading between minor or major versions once a node has joined the cluster on the newer version. The only full rollback path is restoring from PVC snapshots + definitions export taken in Phase 0.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Change Window Recommendation\n\n| Step | Estimated Duration | Risk |\n|------|--------------------|------|\n| Phase 0 (preparation) | 30 min | None (read-only) |\n| Phase 1 (3.12→3.13 rolling) | 15–20 min | Low (rolling, cluster stays up) |\n| Phase 2 (3.13→4.0 rolling) | 15–20 min | Low |\n| Phase 3 (queue migration) | 30–60 min | Medium (requires app coordination) |\n| Phase 4 (validation) | 15 min | None |\n| **Total** | **~2 hours** | |\n\nRecommended: schedule during a low-traffic window with application team on standby for the Phase 3 queue cutover.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2286,"cache_read_input_tokens":33927,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2286},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d869df13-242e-47bf-918e-365de1f8c76b","uuid":"0bd83a77-df44-4523-87cf-856aaa2ce9ac","request_id":"req_011CcPxZ6DcqS6yyJGAVKjfp"}
